2026-03-23 — Race Engineer Mode
==================================

THE INSIGHT

Everyone optimizes training. TTT is the underfloor.

  Training innovations (100+ PRs):  1.224 -> 1.118 = -0.106 BPB
  TTT alone:                        1.118 -> 0.997 = -0.121 BPB

TTT is worth more than all architecture work combined.
But architecture determines HOW MUCH TTT helps:

  Standard arch + AdamW TTT:  -0.019 BPB
  PR #462 arch + AdamW TTT:  -0.053 BPB  (2.8x amplification)
  PROTEUS + LoRA TTT:        -0.121 BPB  (architecture designed for it)

Newey found downforce in the underfloor while everyone polished
the bodywork. We find BPB in the eval budget while everyone
polishes the training loop.

MOVES

1. Get AdamW TTT into train_gpt.py. Can't race without an engine.
2. GEPA-style search on L40S ($0.26/hr). Metric = TTT DELTA.
   Not "best raw BPB" but "most adaptable architecture."
3. sp4096 x TTT compound. 35% more bytes/token = 1.35x multiplier
   on every per-token TTT gain. Nobody has tested this.
4. Budget split: what if 7min train + 3min pre-adapt? Use late
   training time for SAM/MAML/LoRA-init instead of more SGD.
5. Final 8xH100 submission with winning recipe.

RULES

- L40S is for architecture families ONLY
- Never tune LR, warmdown, batch, momentum on proxy
- Primary metric: adaptation_uplift = BPB_no_ttt - BPB_after_ttt
- Rich diagnostics, not scalar scores
- Reflect after each wave, mutate directed

HARDWARE

L40S secure spot, RunPod: $0.26/hr
  6L compiled SDPA: ~306ms/step, ~1960 steps/10min
  11L compiled SDPA: ~585ms/step, ~1025 steps/10min
  Fixed 1500 steps per run (~$0.06-0.09 each)
  No FA3 (Hopper only). No DDP (single GPU). SDPA + compile.

DIAGNOSTICS

Every run logs:
  quant_gap_by_block   — int6 each block solo, measure loss delta
  activation_outliers  — max/mean/std per layer (attn logits + MLP hidden)
  weight_effective_rank — SVD per weight matrix, rank at 90% variance
  adaptation_uplift    — BPB delta from 10ep AdamW TTT
  lora_sensitivity     — SVD proxy: how much can rank-8 capture?
  artifact_bytes       — estimated int6+zstd size
  loss_curve_slope     — final 100 steps trend (descending vs plateau)
  step_time_ms         — sanity only, never optimize for this

EXPERIMENT WAVES

Config shared across all runs:
  TRAIN_BATCH_TOKENS=131072
  TRAIN_SEQ_LEN=1024
  ITERATIONS=1500
  MAX_WALLCLOCK_SECONDS=0
  VAL_TOKENS_LIMIT=1048576
  WARMUP_STEPS=2
  SDPA (no FA3), single GPU, torch.compile

--- Wave 1: Calibrate (4 runs, ~$0.30) ---

Establish baselines. Answer: what's our TTT delta? Does sp4096 amplify it?

  A: 11L sp1024 baseline         -> raw BPB + diagnostics
  B: 11L sp1024 + TTT 10ep       -> TTT delta (this is our reference)
  C: 11L sp4096 baseline         -> raw BPB + diagnostics
  D: 11L sp4096 + TTT 10ep       -> TTT delta (compare to B)

Decision gate: if sp4096 TTT delta > sp1024, lock in sp4096 for later waves.

--- Wave 2: Architecture families (6 runs, ~$0.50) ---

All 11L sp1024 (controlled). Vary one architecture axis per run.
Measure adaptation_uplift + full diagnostics for each.

  E: +SwiGLU (replace relu^2 with silu(x)*linear(x))
  F: +learned sigmoid gating on U-Net skips
     gate = sigmoid(skip_gates[i])
     x = gate*x + (1-gate)*(skip_weights[i]*skip)
  G: +Value Residual (cache V from layer 0, blend into all layers)
  H: +SwiGLU + learned gating combined (PR #462 recipe)
  I: +Gated Attention (per-head sigmoid gate on attn output)
  J: +full MHA (8 KV heads, no GQA)

Rank all by adaptation_uplift. The winner isn't the best raw BPB.
It's the biggest TTT delta.

--- Wave 3: Compound (3-4 runs, ~$0.30) ---

Combine top-2 amplifiers from Wave 2.
Use diagnostics reflection to guide combos:
  - if both amplifiers are quant-friendly (low outliers), combine
  - if one has high effective rank + one has low, they may complement
  - test 2-3 combos of winners

--- Wave 4: sp4096 x winner (2-3 runs, ~$0.20) ---

Apply winning architecture family to sp4096 tokenizer.
Measure compound: does tokenizer multiplier stack with arch amplifier?
If yes, this is our submission recipe.

--- Wave 5: 8xH100 (1-2 runs, ~$7) ---

Full 10-min train. Real batch (786K), real FA3, real DDP.
Tune warmdown/LR HERE, not before.
LoRA TTT 30ep (PROTEUS-style) in remaining eval budget.

Total: ~$5 research + ~$7 submission = ~$12

TTT RECIPE (from PR #462, our starting point)

  optimizer: AdamW(all_params, lr=5e-4, wd=0.0)
  scheduler: CosineAnnealingLR(T_max=10, eta_min=5e-5)
  epochs: 10
  grad_clip: 1.0
  batch: 32 sequences x 1024 tokens
  data: full validation set, sequential chunks
  when: after EMA (if used), before quantization
  measure: sliding window BPB before and after

GEPA LOOP (manual, Claude as reflection LM)

  1. SELECT: pick architecture variant from plan or Pareto front
  2. EXECUTE: run on L40S, collect full diagnostics
  3. REFLECT: Claude reads diagnostics, diagnoses WHY
     - "loss plateau + high activation outliers = quant-unfriendly"
     - "low TTT delta + high effective rank = already well-fit, no room to adapt"
     - "big TTT delta + steep loss curve = undertrained, adaptation fills gaps"
  4. MUTATE: propose next variant based on diagnosis, not random
  5. ACCEPT: if TTT delta improves, add to frontier

Each cycle: one L40S run (~15 min) + 5 min analysis = 20 min.
3 cycles/hr. 15 cycles in an afternoon = $2.

THINGS TO REMEMBER

- We're not forking PROTEUS or PR #462. We're finding our own underfloor.
- sp4096 is our unique angle. Nobody else has submitted it + TTT.
- The architecture that trains best is NOT the architecture that adapts best.
- Flat minima = good TTT. SwiGLU and learned gating may create them.
- MAML (move 4) is high-risk: train to minimize post-TTT loss.
  Needs second-order grads or FOMAML approximation. Expensive.
  Only attempt after Waves 1-4 validate the direction.
